metadata.name: The Past Ahead #253
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Past Ahead by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: The Paradox of Choice #511
metadata.description:
### OVERVIEW ###
This project revisits some of the foundational ideas in my previous work "Above (The Infinite)" and makes them available in a parameterized form for your exploration.

This project both rewards and requires exploration. I intentionally left the parameter space very broad so that edge case configurations would be possible. In practice this means that additional curation beyond the initial random parameters will very likely be required, in a way that mimics my day to day experience as a generative artist.

Thanks to Karsten Schmidt for his excellent thi.ng libraries (https://thi.ng/), which form the technical foundation upon which this work was built.

### CONTROLS ###
e - Save the current frame as a PNG
space - Pause/Resume animation

### PARAMETERS ###
NOTE: Some combinations of parameters will cause flashing/strobing, which is why I have attached the "Epileptic Seizure" label to the project.

* Color Palette: The color palette to apply to the output.
* Merge Technique: The method used to combine the different patterns.
* Patterns: The various patterns that can be combined to form the overall resulting tiled pattern.
* Pattern Scales: The scales used to combine patterns. Higher scale values provide more visible pattern repetition.
* Deformers: An optional additional spatial deformation of a pattern.
* Deformer Scales: The scale of the deformation itself. Lower values use less of the deformation space, while higher values include more.
* Detail: Acts as a filter on the visual complexity of the overall tiled pattern. Lower values will reduce visual complexity, while higher values will increase it.
* Rotation Rate/Scroll Rates: How fast should the image rotate or scroll. Note: adjusting these parameters may result in visuals that trigger motion sickness.
* Zoom: Lower values zoom in, higher values zoom out.
* Round Scales Up?: When checked the pattern scales are rounded up to the nearest integer.
* Animate?: Should some parameters be adjusted with the passing of time?
* Low Res?: When checked, force device pixel density to 1, which reduces strain on the GPU, but may result in graphical artifacts. I usually keep this unchecked unless I want to lighten the load on the GPU.
* Anti-alias?: When checked each pixel will be sampled multiple times to attempt to smooth out possible aliasing. This will put more load on the GPU, and will typically be slower. Can be useful when "Low Res?" is enabled.

### HOWTO ###
Here's how I find interesting things.

First, I lock all of the parameters below "Pattern 3" at their default values. I will also usually lock both Deformers to "Empty", as they can sometimes hide interesting patterns while exploring, and then I experiment with enabling one or both once I have found something interesting.

You can also explore the options individually (to a certain degree) by setting other patterns to "Empty". This can make how patterns affect one another more obvious when you set them.

At this point I'll randomize the parameters, and then do one of the following:

- If I see something that's extremely noisy/detailed, I'll turn down the "Detail" level, which can sometimes smooth things out.

- If a tiling is very tight, I'll lower the "Zoom" to see more of the pattern, or the reverse if I want to see more overview.

- If there's still a lot of aliasing/noise in the image, sometimes enabling anti-aliasing will help, but that will affect performance. I usually try to adjust the Scale/Detail/Zoom before resorting to anti-aliasing.

- Interesting patterns are formed by the scale factors controlling how pattern overlap happens. Sometimes enabling "Round Scales Up?" will introduce some appealing visual symmetry.

- Enable one or both of the deformers to see what impact they have on the pattern.

Finally, once I've found a pattern that's interesting, I may enable scrolling or rotation. Note that enabling additional movement can increase graphical aliasing, so anti-aliasing may be required depending on the pattern.

I hope you enjoy the exploration process!

- Jeff Palmer

metadata.name: Unsquare composition #41

Inspired by Jazz, Unsquare composition I experiments with the notion of non-squared rhythmic forms, where freedom and improvisation take as a premise the idea of an imperfection where we can also find harmony. 

Please do not expect perfect results.

metadata.name: Chop Chop #57
metadata.description:
Chop Chop is a complementary collection to Caterpillars that I prepared to thank my collectors for the amazing love and interest you showed to my work. I did not want to force my way to your wallets with unsolicited thank-you nfts, so all holders of Caterpillars will have a reserve spot to mint at least 1 tokens per wallet for 0 tez ( I dont understand the reserve options fully, sorry - 128 editions reserved for holders of Caterpillars) . 

The holders of this collection will have reserve spots for my next  collection. The reserve spots will be held for one week from minting, and I prefer the unreserved editions to be fair game for anyone, so first come, first served.

I decided to re-work this older project of mine because it was going to take some time for me to prepare an independent and novel collection and also wanted to continue learning new things. The concept is Paul Klee meets Vector Math and Flow Fields, as you can see the visuals are heavily inspired by Paul Klee's work :)

Under the hood, the circles and triangles act as repulsive forces that break and distort the grid, and push the squares in their range out of their way, forming some holes in the fabric created by the same algo that made Caterpillars. 

I have only added one rarity feature which is the palette because this one uses almost all the palettes from Caterpillars (minus neon dreams). I am hoping that this project will not be about rarity, but more like a thank-you gift and an easy way to access my future work.

Well, I hope you will like it...

- Press "s" to save a png.

- Also, 33% royalty split wth the Processing Foundation, % 33 with the minters (if there will be any secondary sales) 

DISCLAIMER :
I am very very new to coding and not very good at this. I have tried to clean up the code as best as I could, and I hope that there is nothing terribly wrong left inside.

metadata.name: ðolmen #11
metadata.description:
ðolmen is a generative art project by Diego Pintos.
It draws rectangles with points instead a plain color or border. With some variations in the distribution of this points, we get a kind of noise depth effect.

12 carefully selected palettes. Based in Art Masterpieces and in Nature.
· Gioconda (Leonardo da Vinci)
· Guernika (Pablo Picasso)
· Nighthawks (Edward Hopper)
· Meninas (Diego Velazquez)
· Judith beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)
· Al Siq (nature)
· guacamayo (nature)
· Salamanca (nature)
· mostaza (nature)
· Timanfaya (nature)
· piedra (nature)
· firefall (nature)

ðolmen builds 10 compositions:
· Square
· PersonChen's Style
· Equilibrium
· Hanging
· Pyramid
· Row
· Column
· 3 columns (randomly aligned)
· 3 rows (randomly aligned)
· Frame

Density
· Tiny: Less than 35 rects. Rare
· Small: Less than 100 rects. Common.
· Medium: Less than 250 rects. Common.
· High: Less than 350 rects. Common.
· Massive: Less than 500 rects. Rare.
· Ultra: More than 500 rects. Rarest.

Rarities
· Rectangle filling type: Filled (95%) or unfilled (5%)
· Monochrome: Just black and white. Always unfilled. (1%)
· Dark mode: Dark background (20%). Dark mode can be monochrome.
· Habitable (90%). See humans later.

Humans
ðolmen can host tiny humans. Contains a little code that draws humans looking down, in order to to provide size perspective.

Minting
Each ðolmen contains all rarities inside. As a ðolmen collector, you can display your final piece in all available formats, and rarity owners can display the regular filled composition. In addition, this can help if you want to print one or more formats.

Tricks and Keys
ðolmen is responsive, you can zoom out your browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas
'd' toggle dark mode
'f' toggle fill mode
'm' toggle monochrome

More info and visual description:
https://thelirios.com/dolmen/

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Circles #115
metadata.description:
“Circles” is a set of generative artwork make by sophisticatedly designed algorithm with surprising randomness. It explores different combinations of size, shape, color, arrangement, etc., trying to create different feeling about circles. 

I like circle because it’s a metaphor to the cycle of life, we start at one point and end at the same point. No matter the circle is big or small, thick or thin，colorful or dull, we experience it as a cycle.

Press the ’s’ key to save the image to your computer.

#This is the republish version of "Circle" as the old version contain a bug so I have to disable it. All holders have been refunded.

#For apology, the first 100 editions will be free for minting. And then there will be price increase every time when another 100 mints complete.

metadata.name: Bloc.Plan #39
metadata.description:
Working as an architect and interior designer daily, I always find that creating space is something interesting. Especially a block plan. As an architectural drawing, it serves to inform the viewer of the presence or absence of a space by composing positive and negative spaces on the site. Through this, I found out that block plan can be a captivating visual art as well.

Press [s] to save captured image

created using p5.js
dirbots - Aug22
